DMTV Milkshake: Mastering the Art of ‘Interior Marketing’ \\\
For this week’s Milkshake, we spoke to @leiatward, founder and principal of home staging firm @ltwdesign. Selling a house? Buying a house? Wondering about the “one weird trick” of staging a home? Leia has the inside scoop on how to max out your asking price — even if it means a change-up from your beloved trad decor to something more … transitional, plus why you’re going to have to say goodbye to those rugs (at least for a moment). \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

node.text: Surfing is an exciting sport to take up or even just watch from the shorelines, but it comes with an environmental cost. In the UK, according to Keep Britain Tidy, an estimated 16,000+ cheap, polystyrene bodyboards are abandoned on UK beaches, often after just a single use. Not only does this add plastic to our oceans, but it also endangers wildlife who swallow bits and pieces that float in the waters or get tangled up in seaweed. Student designer Harry Peck from Northumbria University wants to minimize this problem by upcycling the foam material into durable furniture. Thus, his final project, Wave Cycle, was created. 🌊 \\\ Read more about @harrypeckstudio and Wave Cycle at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: DAWN is the solo debut of Italian sculptor and architect Umberto Bellardi Ricci (@butrome), unveiled at @matterstore. Influenced by the designer’s architecture practice as well as his training in social services, each home furnishing is interconnected with the environment it resides in. Ricci’s monumental forms are further indulged through the use of elevated materials, whether it be bronze in his seating, travertine in the coffee table or Dedar’s bouclé as upholstery. The modular lighting uses strategically folded aluminum to create warmth through refraction. \\\ Read more about DAWN at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: Patinated copper is a beautiful thing, but the process can take years to occur. Furniture company @massproductions recently found inspiration for their new Oilcloth Green color in the natural chemical process of patination, as well as the white-green leaves of the willow tree. “For us, it is important that an outdoor piece of furniture can be in nature without creating too much visual clutter. It is a challenge that requires a certain fingertip feeling. A color that in the indoor environment can appear pale, becomes very strong in full daylight amongst nature’s slightly duller color scale,” says Magnus Elebäck, CEO and co-founder of Massproductions. \\\ Read more about the new Oilcloth Green hue from Massproductions at the link in bio. 🔗
